1) Gathering data.
2) Preparing data.
3) Choosing a model.
4) Training it. --> 80% for training 20% for testing.

6) Hyper parameter tuning.
7) Prediction.


Training:

Y(Output)= M(Slope) * X(Input) + B(Intercept)

M & B are the values are to adjust.

Weights --> M--> [] There may be many M's (Features) M1,M2 etc.
Biasis --> B --> []

repeat it for accuracy.
Training --> [W,b] --> Prediction.

Hi everyone, i'm a a Software Engineering student graduating in Italy and I love Machine Learning.

How many times, trying to approach Machine Learning, you felt baffled, disoriented and without a real "path" to follow, to ensure yourself a deep knowledge and the ability to apply it?

This field is crazily exciting, but being rapid and "new" at the same time, it can be confusing to understand what each things means, and have a coherent naming of the things across resources and tutorials.

I recently landed my first internship for a Data Science position in a shiny ML startup. My boss asked me if it was possible to create a study path for me and newcomers, and i've put a lot of efforts to share my 4-5 years of walking around the internet and collecting sources, projects, awesome tools, tutorial, links, best practices in the ML field, and organizing them in a awesome and useable way.

You will get your hands dirty and learn in parallel theory and practice (which is the only efffective way to learn).

The frameworks i've chosen is Scikit-Learn for generic ML tasks and TensorFlow for Deep Learning, and I'll update the document weekly.

No prior knowledge is required, just time and will.

Feel free to improve it and share with everyone.

Inb4: sorry for my english, it's not my native language :)

*quick summary:*
- machine learning is all about seeing some examples of input-output pairs and then being able to predict the output for new inputs
- basically, you feed a bunch of examples to a machine, and the machine will start to learn about the defining characteristics of your examples
- therefore, it is extremely import that you feed it good examples! Generally, the more examples the better, but you also want your examples to have the distinguishing features in them.
- once you gather some good examples (with distinguishing features), you generally clean it up, plot it, do some statistical analysis, etc
- then you choose one of the many different machine learning models (e.g. linear, neural network, etc). Each has its pros/cons. Depending on your examples, and your time constraints, you will pick one of these models
- you will then tune some parameters of the model (again how you do this depends on your examples and time constraints)

I Think I love you , your course, and Google as well! Many thanks for these delightful lessons. Though May I ask a question?
Shouldn't it be better if we only teach our model one object at a time? If we can only give various types of beers (because there are  lots of them already) hence, sharpening the recognition of object "beer" instead of distorting the learning process (and resources as well) with the wine recognition that is already mixed with the beer recognition!

If I am wrong, please correct me, and specify what is truly wrong. Thanks Again!

One object at a time uses way too many resources. Typically batching is used to feed the model multiple objects at once. A secondary problem which may arise is if you train it only on the beer objects first then the model will only learn to predict beer. If wine is suddenly introduced the model will take a long time to re-assign/adjust the parameters to correctly classify wine. 

What could possibly work is if you train a net exclusively on beer and then use that net as a basis for predicting wine (transfer learning). For that, however, certain features of the objects need to overlap. Here alcohol content could be used as it is a feature of both.

The hype does not come from what he explained. The difference from plain old AI to what is now the hype is not what you can see in the video. Machine learning can do much more. If you go more in depth and read a lot of papers you will find out more about convolutional neuronal nets etc.. Imagine stacking a bunch of layers (like explained in the video) on top of each others building a complex network where not just one simple function but very complex n dimensional functions will be solved concerning different parts and interpretations of (e.g.) an image in a matter of seconds formulating a general solution for complex real world problems. Yes... it is partially about GPU-power increase, but not solely. Also about the detection of complex layer structures that maximally use the potential of this basic machine learning mechanism.

3Blue1Brown's videos, from what I've seen, are the most clearly explained on YouTube. Siraj doesn't often take time to explain concepts well enough, as well as barely skipping through code, so it's not good for people who don't already have a good grasp of machine learning (which makes those videos almost pointless imo). An alternative is sentdex, but even he sometimes doesn't explain things as deeply as 3Blue1Brown does in such an easily-digestible way. He is still a very good resource for learning computer vision libraries and some ML libraries as well though, since he does all of the coding live and takes breaks to explain things like what functions do, what parameters they should take, etc.

so far, 3Blue1Brown is killing it. I was hoping Dan Shiffman will continue the journey to building a js-based library soon. but for now, I will continue to awe myself with 3Blue1Brown's offering. although i still watch Siraj for the dank memes and Dan Shiffman for the fun! :)
